While the typical range of dynamic  markings is from {{serif|'''''ppp'''''}} to {{serif|'''''fff'''''}}, some pieces use additional markings of further emphasis. Extreme dynamic markings imply an extreme range of loudness, or, alternatively, imply an extremely subtle distinction between very small differences of loudness within a normal range. This kind of usage is most common in orchestral works from the late 19th-century onwards. Generally, these markings are supported by the [[orchestration]] of the work, with heavy forte markings brought to life by having many loud instruments like brass and percussion playing at once.

In [[Gustav Holst|Holst]]'s ''[[The Planets]]'', {{serif|'''''ffff'''''}} occurs twice in "Mars" and once in "Uranus", often punctuated by organ.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/5/59/IMSLP05396-Holst_-_THE_PLANETS_-_Suite_for_Large_Orchestra_-_Partitur.pdf|title=The Planets|last=Holst|first=Gustav|publisher=Goodwin & Tabb|year=1921|isbn=|location=London|pages=29, 42, 159|access-date=25 April 2018}}</ref>  [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]] marks a bassoon solo {{serif|'''''pppppp'''''}} (6 {{serif|'''''p'''''}}s) in his [[Symphony No. 6 (Tchaikovsky)|''Pathétique'' Symphony]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/b/b5/IMSLP504312-PMLP2511-Tchaikovsky_-_Symphony_No.6_in_B_minor,_Op.74;_TH_30;_CW_27,_'Pathetic'.pdf|title=Fourth, Fifth and Sixth Symphonies in Full Score|last=Tchaikovsky|first=Peter Ilyitch|publisher=Dover Publications|year=1979|isbn=048623861X|location=New York|page=First movement, just before Allegro vivo|nopp=y|oclc=6414366}}</ref> and uses {{serif|'''''ffff'''''}} in passages of his ''[[1812 Overture]]''<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/f/f1/IMSLP01078-Tchaikovsky_-_1812_Overture.pdf|title=P.I. Tchaikovsky: Complete Collected Works, Vol. 25|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|editor-last=Nikolayev|editor-first=Aleksandr|location=|pages=79|access-date=25 April 2018}}</ref> and his [[Symphony No. 5 (Tchaikovsky)|Fifth Symphony]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/b/b6/IMSLP504184-PMLP2739-combinepdf_(1).pdf|title=Fourth, Fifth and Sixth Symphonies in Full Score|last=Tchaikovsky|first=Peter Ilyich|date=1979|publisher=Dover Publications|year=|isbn=048623861X|location=New York|pages=18, 65 [on PDF]|oclc=6414366}}</ref> The baritone passage "Era la notte" from [[Verdi]]'s opera ''[[Otello (Verdi)|Otello]]'' uses {{serif|'''''pppp'''''}}, though the same spot is marked {{serif|'''''ppp'''''}} in the full score.<ref>(1965). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=GfIEAAAAMAAJ&q=pensato+webern&dq=pensato+webern&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjr7uunheXUAhVK6YMKHSUjARkQ6AEIRTAG The Musical Times]'', Vol. 106. Novello.</ref> [[Igor Stravinsky]] used {{serif|'''''ffff'''''}} at the end of the finale of the [[The Firebird#1919 Suite|1919 ''Firebird Suite'']].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://petruccilibrary.us/scores/Stravinsky_Igor_1971/Stravinsky%20-%20Firebird%20Suite%201919%20(orch.%20score).pdf|title=FIrebird Suite|last=Strawinsky|first=Igor|publisher=Boosey & Hawkes|year=|isbn=|location=New York|pages=80|access-date=25 April 2018}}</ref> [[Sergei Vasilievich Rachmaninoff|Sergei Rachmaninoff]] uses {{serif|'''''sffff'''''}} in his [[Prelude in C-sharp minor (Rachmaninoff)|Prelude in C{{music|sharp}}, Op. 3 No. 2]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/1/1e/IMSLP273032-PMLP05664-Rachmaninoff_Album_Book_1_op.3.pdf|title=Album Book I. Op. 3, Nos. 1–5|last=Rachmaninoff|first=Sergei|publisher=Augener|year=1911|isbn=|editor-last=Thümer|editor-first=Otto Gustav|location=London|pages=5|access-date=25 April 2018}}</ref> [[Gustav Mahler]], in the third movement of his [[Symphony No. 7 (Mahler)|Seventh Symphony]], gives the celli and basses a marking of {{serif|'''''fffff'''''}} (5 {{serif|'''''f'''''}}s), along with a footnote directing '[[Bartok pizzicato|pluck so hard that the strings hit the wood]]'.{{efn|So stark anreißen, daß die Saiten an das Holz anschlagen.}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/a/a8/IMSLP138638-SIBLEY1802.16651.a3b6-39087009455132score.pdf|title=Symphonie No. 7|last=Mahler|first=Gustav|publisher=Eulenburg|year=1909|isbn=|location=Leipzig|pages=229|access-date=26 April 2018}}</ref> On the other extreme, [[Carl Nielsen]], in the second movement of his [[Symphony No. 5 (Nielsen)|Fifth Symphony]], marked a passage for woodwinds a diminuendo to {{serif|'''''ppppp'''''}} (5 {{serif|'''''p'''''}}s).<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ks.imslp.info/files/imglnks/usimg/3/38/IMSLP92727-PMLP53439-Nielsen-Symph5SCce.pdf|title=Vaerker, Series II, No.5|last=Nielson|first=Carl|publisher=|year=|isbn=|editor-last=Fjeldsøe|editor-first=Michael|location=|pages=128|access-date=26 April 2018}}</ref> [[György Ligeti]] uses extreme dynamics in his [[Études (Ligeti)|Piano Études]]: Étude No. 9 (''Vertige'') ends with a diminuendo to {{serif|'''''pppppppp'''''}} (8 {{serif|'''''p'''''}}s),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YI-TWpEgGTM|title=György Ligeti - Études for Piano (Book 2), No. 9 [3/9]|last=|first=|date=|website=[[YouTube]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=26 April 2018|time=3:34}}</ref> while Étude No. 13 (''L'Escalier du Diable'') contains a passage marked {{serif|'''''ffffff'''''}} (6 {{serif|'''''f'''''}}s) that progresses to a {{serif|'''''ffffffff'''''}} (8 {{serif|'''''f'''''}}s).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q6LmG9myHxA|title=György Ligeti - Études for Piano (Book 2), No. 13 [7/9]|last=|first=|date=|website=[[YouTube]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=26 April 2018|time=5:12–5:14}}</ref><!--please don't add the Florentiner Marsch; while that Tumblr post is admittedly hilarious, the actual score does not actually have that many f's. Only two of them-->

==History==
''On Music'', one of the ''[[Moralia]]'' attributed to the philosopher [[Plutarch]] in the first century AD, suggests that ancient Greek musical performance included dynamic transitions – though dynamics receive far less attention in the text than does [[rhythm]] or [[harmony]].

The [[renaissance music|Renaissance]] [[composer]] [[Giovanni Gabrieli]] was one of the first to indicate dynamics in [[music notation]], but dynamics were used sparingly by composers until the late 18th century. [[Johann Sebastian Bach|J.S. Bach]] used some dynamic terms, including ''forte'', ''piano'', ''più piano'', and ''pianissimo'' (although written out as full words), and in some cases it may be that {{serif|'''''ppp'''''}} was considered to mean ''pianissimo'' in this period.

The fact that the [[harpsichord]] could play only "terraced" dynamics (either loud or soft, but not in between), and the fact that composers of the period did not mark gradations of dynamics in their scores, has led to the "somewhat misleading suggestion that [[Baroque music|baroque]] dynamics are 'terraced dynamics'," writes [[Robert Donington]].<ref>[[Robert Donington|Donington, Robert]]: ''Baroque Music'' (1982) WW Norton, 1982. {{ISBN|0-393-30052-8}}. Page 32.</ref> In fact, baroque musicians constantly varied dynamics: in 1752, [[Johann Joachim Quantz]] wrote that "Light and shade must be constantly introduced ... by the incessant interchange of loud and soft."<ref>Donington, Robert: ''Baroque Music'' (1982) WW Norton, 1982. {{ISBN|0-393-30052-8}}. Page 33.</ref> In addition to this, the [[harpsichord]] in fact becomes louder or softer depending on the thickness of the musical texture (four notes are louder than two). This allowed composers like J.S. Bach to build dynamics directly into their compositions, without the need for notation.

In the [[Romantic music|Romantic period]], composers greatly expanded the vocabulary for describing dynamic changes in their scores. Where [[Joseph Haydn|Haydn]] and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]] specified six levels ({{serif|'''''pp'''''}} to {{serif|'''''ff'''''}}), [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]] used also {{serif|'''''ppp'''''}} and {{serif|'''''fff'''''}} (the latter less frequently), and [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]] used a range of terms to describe the dynamics he wanted. In the slow movement of Brahms's [[Horn Trio (Brahms)|trio for violin, horn and piano (Opus 40)]], he uses the expressions {{serif|'''''ppp'''''}}, ''molto piano'', and ''[[quasi niente]]'' to express different qualities of quiet. Many Romantic and later composers added ''{{serif|più '''p'''}}'' and ''{{serif|più '''f'''}}'', making for a total of ten levels between {{serif|'''''ppp'''''}} and {{serif|'''''fff'''''}}.

== Relation to audio dynamics ==
The introduction of modern recording techniques has provided alternative ways to control the dynamics of music. [[Dynamic range compression]] is used to control the [[Dynamic range#Music|dynamic range]] of a recording, or a single instrument. This can affect loudness variations, both at the micro-<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mastering Audio|last=Katz|first=Robert|publisher=|year=2002|isbn=0-240-80545-3|location=Amsterdam: Boston|pages=109}}</ref> and macro scale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.soundonsound.com/sound-advice/dynamic-range-loudness-war|title='Dynamic Range' & The Loudness War|last=Deruty|first=Emmanuel|date=September 2011|work=Sound on Sound|access-date=2018-01-16|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> In many contexts, the meaning of the term ''dynamics'' is therefore not immediately clear. To distinguish between the different aspects of dynamics, the term ''performed dynamics'' can be used to refer to the aspects of music dynamics that is controlled exclusively by the performer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Elowsson|first=Anders|last2=Friberg|first2=Anders|date=|title=Predicting the perception of performed dynamics in music audio with ensemble learning|url=http://www.speech.kth.se/prod/publications/files/4106.pdf|journal=The Acoustical Society of America|volume=141 |issue=3|pages=2224–2242|via=}}</ref>

